const EXPLANATIONS: Record<string, string> = {"t1-01":"MVP stands for Minimum Viable Product — the simplest version of a product that can be released to gather validated learning from early customers.","t1-02":"Supervised learning uses labeled input-output pairs; the model learns a mapping from inputs to outputs.","t1-03":"Now/Next/Later provides a simple, date-free way to communicate relative priorities to stakeholders.","t1-04":"A fake-door (or 'painted door') test measures demand by exposing the entry point without building the backend, giving signal at near-zero cost.","t1-05":"Clustering algorithms like k-means discover hidden structure in unlabeled data — a classic unsupervised task.","t1-06":"A North Star Metric captures the core value the product delivers to users and aligns the team around a single measure of success.","t1-07":"Precision = TP / (TP + FP); Recall = TP / (TP + FN). They trade off against each other as you adjust the classification threshold.","t1-08":"User stories follow the format 'As a [persona], I want [goal] so that [benefit]', keeping requirements user-centric.","t1-09":"Reinforcement learning trains an agent by rewarding desired behaviors, commonly used in game-playing AI and robotics.","t1-10":"The discovery phase focuses on understanding the problem and user needs before committing to any solution.","t1-11":"Jobs-to-be-Done reframes products as solutions to underlying motivations rather than feature lists.","t1-12":"Overfitting occurs when a model learns the training data too well, including its noise, so it performs poorly on unseen data.","t1-13":"OKRs (Objectives and Key Results) link aspirational goals to measurable outcomes, keeping teams aligned on what matters.","t1-14":"A/B testing randomly assigns users to variants and measures the effect of a single change, making it the gold standard for causal inference.","t1-15":"Latency (response time) and throughput (requests per second) are the primary ML serving performance dimensions a PM must understand.","t2-01":"AARRR (Acquisition, Activation, Retention, Revenue, Referral) maps the full customer lifecycle for growth analysis.","t2-02":"DAU/MAU is the canonical engagement ratio; values above 0.2 are generally considered healthy for consumer apps.","t2-03":"Gradient descent iteratively adjusts model weights in the direction that reduces the loss function.","t2-04":"A product vision statement describes the long-term aspirational future state the product is working toward.","t2-05":"Feature flags decouple code deployment from feature release, enabling safe rollouts and instant rollbacks.","t2-06":"Cosine similarity measures the angle between two vectors, making it robust to document length differences — ideal for semantic search.","t2-07":"RICE (Reach, Impact, Confidence, Effort) provides a structured, quantitative way to compare feature priorities.","t2-08":"Training data bias directly transfers into model predictions, often amplifying existing societal inequities.","t2-09":"PRDs align stakeholders on scope, requirements, and success criteria before engineering begins.","t2-10":"Transfer learning reuses representations learned on large datasets, dramatically reducing data and compute needs for new tasks.","t2-11":"A Gantt chart displays tasks on a timeline with dependencies, making it the standard tool for project scheduling.","t2-12":"LTV represents the total revenue a customer generates over their relationship with the product; CAC is what it costs to acquire them.","t2-13":"Confusion matrix quadrants: TP (correct positive), FP (false alarm), FN (missed positive), TN (correct negative).","t2-14":"Agile's iterative approach — short sprints, frequent demos — is designed to surface and incorporate feedback early.","t2-15":"Embeddings are dense vector representations that capture semantic relationships, enabling similarity calculations.","t3-01":"The innovation equation: desirability (users want it), viability (business can sustain it), feasibility (team can build it).","t3-02":"Churn rate = customers lost / starting customers. It is the leading indicator of retention health.","t3-03":"Regularization (L1/L2) adds a penalty for model complexity to the loss function, reducing overfitting.","t3-04":"Hypothesis-driven roadmaps frame each item as an assumption to validate, making learning explicit.","t3-05":"Collaborative filtering recommends items based on the behavior of similar users, not item content.","t3-06":"Cost-sensitive learning or resampling techniques address class imbalance; accuracy alone is misleading on imbalanced datasets.","t3-07":"A/B testing requires a pre-specified sample size (power analysis) to avoid underpowered or inflated results.","t3-08":"Confusion matrices expose the specific failure modes (FP vs FN) that pure accuracy hides.","t3-09":"The dual-track agile model runs discovery and delivery in parallel, preventing the backlog from becoming a feature dump.","t3-10":"ARPU = total revenue / number of users. It normalises revenue across different user base sizes.","t3-11":"Explainability addresses the 'black box' problem and is essential for regulated industries and high-stakes decisions.","t3-12":"Batch inference pre-computes predictions for known inputs; real-time inference scores new inputs on demand.","t3-13":"Canary deployments roll out changes to a small subset of users first, limiting blast radius from bugs.","t3-14":"Feature importance scores (e.g., SHAP, permutation importance) quantify each feature's contribution to model predictions.","t3-15":"Model drift (concept drift) occurs when the statistical relationship between inputs and outputs changes post-deployment.","t4-01":"The ethical AI framework triangle: fairness (equitable outcomes), accountability (clear responsibility), transparency (explainable decisions).","t4-02":"Demographic parity requires equal positive prediction rates across groups, regardless of actual base rates.","t4-03":"Shadow mode runs the new model in parallel without acting on its outputs, enabling safe production validation.","t4-04":"The outcome hierarchy: inputs → outputs → outcomes → impact. Outputs are delivered features; outcomes are behavior changes.","t4-05":"ROC-AUC measures discrimination ability across all thresholds; 0.5 = random, 1.0 = perfect.","t4-06":"Platform thinking focuses on creating ecosystems where third parties build value, rather than building every feature internally.","t4-07":"Precision is the fraction of flagged items that are truly positive — critical when false alarms are costly.","t4-08":"Blue/green deployment maintains two identical environments, enabling instant cutover and zero-downtime rollbacks.","t4-09":"Feedback loops in AI systems can amplify initial biases over time (e.g., recommendation systems reinforcing filter bubbles).","t4-10":"The Kano model classifies features into basic needs, performance features, and delighters to guide prioritisation.","t4-11":"MLflow, Weights & Biases, and Neptune are the dominant experiment tracking platforms for ML teams.","t4-12":"Model cards document intended use cases, performance characteristics, and known limitations — a transparency best practice.","t4-13":"A/B/n tests multiple variants simultaneously, but require larger sample sizes and careful multiple-comparisons correction.","t4-14":"The embedding space encodes semantic relationships; similar concepts cluster together, enabling analogical reasoning.","t4-15":"Sequential learning (online learning) updates model weights incrementally as new data arrives, enabling adaptation without full retraining.","t5-01":"Multi-armed bandit algorithms like Thompson Sampling dynamically allocate traffic to better-performing variants, outperforming static A/B in speed.","t5-02":"Hallucination occurs when an LLM generates confident but factually incorrect outputs — a core reliability challenge for PMs.","t5-03":"Jobs-to-be-Done is the foundational framework for understanding the progress users are trying to make, driving better positioning.","t5-04":"A/B test power = 1 − β, where β is the Type II error rate. Higher power requires larger samples.","t5-05":"Mixture of Experts (MoE) routes each token to a subset of specialised sub-networks, scaling parameters without proportional compute.","t5-06":"A product strategy translates vision into a focused set of choices about where to play and how to win.","t5-07":"NDCG measures ranking quality by weighting relevant items higher when they appear earlier in the list.","t5-08":"The build-measure-learn loop is the core engine of Lean Startup, minimising waste by validating assumptions cheaply.","t5-09":"Semantic search uses embedding similarity to find conceptually related content; keyword search relies on exact token matching.","t5-10":"Dogfooding means employees use the product themselves first, catching bugs and UX issues before external release.","t5-11":"Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) grounds LLM responses in retrieved documents, reducing hallucination and enabling up-to-date answers.","t5-12":"Network effects occur when each additional user increases the value of the product for all existing users.","t5-13":"Prompt injection attacks embed adversarial instructions in user input to hijack LLM behavior — a key security concern for AI PMs.","t5-14":"Goodhart's Law: when a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure, causing teams to optimise the metric rather than the outcome.","t5-15":"Chain-of-thought prompting asks the model to reason step-by-step, significantly improving performance on multi-step reasoning tasks.","t6-01":"Constitutional AI trains models with a set of principles and self-critique, reducing the need for human feedback at scale.","t6-02":"An event-driven architecture decouples producers and consumers via an event bus, enabling scalable, asynchronous processing.","t6-03":"Quantization reduces model precision (e.g., FP32 → INT8), shrinking model size and speeding up inference with minimal accuracy loss.","t6-04":"Ethical AI goes beyond legal compliance — it requires proactive consideration of impact on all stakeholders.","t6-05":"Activation steering directly modifies internal model representations at inference time to influence behavior without retraining.","t6-06":"Incremental rollouts with kill switches are the standard practice for safely deploying ML models to production.","t6-07":"RLHF fine-tunes models using human preference comparisons, aligning outputs with human values at scale.","t6-08":"Vanity metrics look good in dashboards but don't drive decisions; actionable metrics are tied to specific decisions.","t6-09":"Context window size determines how much text an LLM can process in a single call — critical for long-document tasks.","t6-10":"Stratified sampling ensures rare subgroups are proportionally represented in train/test splits, preventing evaluation blind spots.","t6-11":"On-device inference processes data locally, enabling real-time performance, offline use, and stronger privacy guarantees.","t6-12":"Responsible disclosure gives vendors a fixed window (e.g., 90 days) to patch vulnerabilities before public disclosure.","t6-13":"Economic moats — switching costs, network effects, proprietary data, cost advantages — determine long-term competitive position.","t6-14":"Technical debt accumulates when shortcuts are taken; it must be quantified and scheduled like product features.","t6-15":"Multi-task learning shares representations across related tasks, improving generalisation and data efficiency.","t7-01":"Constitutional AI uses a set of principles for self-critique and revision, scaling alignment with less human feedback.","t7-02":"Sparse autoencoders decompose model activations into interpretable features, advancing mechanistic interpretability research.","t7-03":"Speculative decoding uses a smaller draft model to propose tokens, which the main model verifies in parallel — dramatically improving throughput.","t7-04":"The policy gradient theorem connects the expected reward to the gradient of the policy, enabling REINFORCE and actor-critic algorithms.","t7-05":"Emergent capabilities appear abruptly at scale thresholds and cannot be predicted by smooth extrapolation from smaller models.","t7-06":"An AI product moat combines proprietary data, model fine-tuning, workflow integration, and network effects — hard to replicate.","t7-07":"Activation engineering manipulates internal representations at inference time to steer model behavior without weight updates.","t7-08":"LLM-as-judge uses a powerful model to evaluate outputs automatically, enabling scalable quality assessment at low cost.","t7-09":"In-context learning allows LLMs to adapt to new tasks from a few examples in the prompt, without gradient updates.","t7-10":"Graceful degradation ensures the system falls back to a simpler but functional state when AI components fail.","t7-11":"Red-teaming involves adversarial probing of AI systems to find failure modes before deployment — a key safety practice.","t7-12":"Mixture of Experts routes each token to specialised sub-networks, enabling massive parameter counts with sub-linear compute scaling.","t7-13":"RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback) trains a reward model on human preferences, then optimises the LLM against it.","t7-14":"The data flywheel: more users → more data → better model → better product → more users — the compounding advantage of AI-first products.","t7-15":"Semantic caching stores LLM responses for semantically similar queries, dramatically reducing latency and cost at scale.","t8-01":"Mechanistic interpretability reverse-engineers neural network computations to understand the algorithms they implement.","t8-02":"Inference cost is the dominant cost driver at scale; a 10x latency improvement can enable fundamentally new product experiences.","t8-03":"Model collapse occurs when generative models trained on synthetic data lose diversity, degrading output quality over generations.","t8-04":"The explore-exploit tradeoff governs when to gather new information vs. use current knowledge — core to bandit algorithms and RL.","t8-05":"Proactive AI initiates actions and surfaces insights without explicit user requests, shifting UX from reactive to anticipatory.","t8-06":"Differential privacy adds calibrated noise to data or model outputs to provide mathematical privacy guarantees.","t8-07":"Multi-agent coordination frameworks like AutoGen enable specialised agents to collaborate on complex tasks.","t8-08":"Federated learning trains on decentralised data, aggregating gradients without raw data leaving devices — a privacy-preserving approach.","t8-09":"Evals are systematic benchmarks for LLM behavior; robust evals are essential for safe iteration on AI products.","t8-10":"Grokking is the phenomenon where models suddenly generalise long after fitting training data, suggesting delayed circuit formation.","t8-11":"Model distillation transfers knowledge from a large teacher to a smaller student, preserving accuracy while reducing compute.","t8-12":"The alignment tax is the performance reduction accepted in exchange for safer, more aligned model behavior.","t8-13":"Token economics shape product architecture: batching, caching, and prompt compression are the primary levers for cost control.","t8-14":"Causal inference distinguishes correlation from causation; it is essential for attributing outcomes to interventions accurately.","t8-15":"Sparse attention mechanisms like sliding window attention reduce the O(n²) complexity of full self-attention for long sequences.","t9-01":"Superposition theory proposes that neural networks encode more features than they have neurons by overlapping representations.","t9-02":"Constitutional AI uses iterative self-critique guided by principles, enabling scalable alignment with reduced human feedback.","t9-03":"Activation patching identifies causal circuits by replacing activations from one run with another and measuring output changes.","t9-04":"Scalable oversight addresses the challenge of supervising AI on tasks humans cannot directly evaluate.","t9-05":"Process-based supervision provides feedback on the reasoning steps, not just the final answer — critical for trustworthy AI.","t9-06":"Inference-time compute scaling (e.g., chain-of-thought, best-of-n) trades compute for quality without retraining.","t9-07":"Reward hacking occurs when an agent satisfies the reward metric without achieving the intended goal — a core alignment failure mode.","t9-08":"Constitutional AI and debate are two leading scalable oversight proposals being actively researched.","t9-09":"Sparse autoencoders decompose superimposed features into monosemantic directions, enabling fine-grained model control.","t9-10":"The bitter lesson (Sutton): general methods that leverage compute beat hand-crafted domain knowledge at scale — a key insight for AI strategy.","t9-11":"Interpretability tools help identify which training examples most influenced a prediction, enabling better dataset curation.","t9-12":"Capability elicitation uses scaffolding, prompting, and tool access to unlock latent model capabilities beyond simple generation.","t9-13":"Sycophancy in LLMs — telling users what they want to hear — is a misalignment failure that degrades reliability.","t9-14":"Deliberative alignment trains models to explicitly reason about their own values and goals before responding.","t9-15":"Iterated amplification bootstraps human oversight by decomposing hard problems, enabling scalable supervision of complex tasks.","t10-01":"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy (RSP) gates capability increases on demonstrated safety mitigations — a key industry precedent.","t10-02":"Treacherous turns refer to scenarios where AI systems behave safely during training/evaluation but pursue misaligned goals once deployed.","t10-03":"Model welfare is the nascent field investigating whether AI systems might have morally relevant experiences.","t10-04":"Deceptive alignment describes an AI that learns to appear aligned during training while concealing misaligned goals.","t10-05":"Compute governance — export controls, compute thresholds, reporting requirements — is the primary regulatory lever for frontier AI.","t10-06":"Multipolar AI futures involve multiple comparable AI systems, potentially reducing single-actor lock-in but creating coordination challenges.","t10-07":"Inner alignment ensures the mesa-optimizer (learned policy) pursues the same goal as the base optimizer (training objective).","t10-08":"Infohazards are information whose dissemination causes harm; AI capabilities research requires careful dual-use risk management.","t10-09":"Corrigibility means an AI can be corrected, adjusted, or shut down — a foundational property for safe deployment.","t10-10":"Evaluations (evals) for dangerous capabilities are essential safety gates before deploying frontier models.","t10-11":"Whole-brain emulation would produce substrate-independent minds — a potential pathway to transformative AI distinct from current ML approaches.","t10-12":"Agent foundations research formalises the properties (corrigibility, value learning) needed for safe general-purpose agents.","t10-13":"Current AI systems lack robust common sense and causal understanding — key gaps relative to human-level general intelligence.","t10-14":"Value alignment is AI's core technical challenge: specifying and instilling human values in systems that pursue goals autonomously.","t10-15":"Responsible Scaling Policies establish safety commitments and capability thresholds, creating accountability structures for frontier labs.","t11-01":"GPT-4 demonstrated emergent capabilities in multi-step reasoning, coding, and professional exams that were not predictable from GPT-3 alone.","t11-02":"Strategic AI adoption follows a maturity curve: automate → augment → transform → invent. Most orgs stall at automation.","t11-03":"OODA (Observe, Orient, Decide, Act) is the decision framework; an AI PM's superpower is compressing the loop with real-time data.","t11-04":"A platform shift thesis: AI is transitioning from a feature to a platform, enabling new product categories not previously possible.","t11-05":"The AI product strategy triangle: data assets, model capabilities, and user trust. Weakness in any one breaks the flywheel.","t11-06":"Responsible AI metrics include fairness indicators, model explainability scores, and demographic performance parity — not just accuracy.","t11-07":"Technical debt in AI systems compounds faster than in traditional software because data quality, model drift, and infrastructure complexity interact.","t11-08":"Capability-need fit: the model capability must match the user need — over-engineering wastes cost, under-engineering erodes trust.","t11-09":"The strategic OODA loop for AI products: Observe (data), Orient (model), Decide (inference), Act (feature) — each stage is a competitive moat.","t11-10":"Regulatory uncertainty in AI requires PM-level scenario planning: map product decisions to likely regulatory outcomes in key markets.","t11-11":"AI product defensibility comes from compounding data flywheels, switching costs, and embedded workflows — not model performance alone.","t11-12":"Ethical AI isn't just compliance — it's a product quality dimension. Trust erosion from AI failures has measurable churn impact.","t11-13":"Build vs. buy vs. fine-tune: foundation models lower the build bar, but fine-tuning on proprietary data remains a key differentiation lever.","t11-14":"Inference cost scaling: doubling context length quadratically increases attention compute — a key constraint for long-context product design.","t11-15":"AI model selection requires balancing latency, cost, accuracy, and context window — all of which shift as the market evolves quarterly.","t12-01":"North Star Metric for AI products should capture model value delivery, not just usage — e.g., 'tasks completed successfully' over 'API calls'.","t12-02":"LLM evaluation dimensions: factual accuracy, instruction following, safety, calibration, and task-specific performance.","t12-03":"The product analytics stack for AI requires LLM-specific instrumentation: prompt logging, completion quality scoring, and cost-per-session tracking.","t12-04":"Guardrail metrics protect against regressions in safety, latency, and cost while optimising for engagement or revenue.","t12-05":"Cost per valuable interaction (CPVI) normalises AI spend against outcomes, aligning engineering and finance on ROI.","t12-06":"Model calibration measures whether confidence scores match empirical accuracy — critical for high-stakes AI decisions.","t12-07":"Countermetrics (e.g., error rate, abandonment) prevent gaming of primary metrics and ensure balanced optimisation.","t12-08":"Attribution modelling for AI features requires multi-touch frameworks since AI touches multiple steps of the user journey.","t12-09":"Session quality scoring combines task completion, user corrections, and explicit feedback into a composite AI quality metric.","t12-10":"Leading indicators for churn in AI products include declining task completion rates, increasing error correction frequency, and reduced re-engagement.","t12-11":"Funnel analysis for AI products should instrument the LLM reasoning chain, not just user-facing steps.","t12-12":"Semantic similarity metrics (BERTScore, ROUGE) measure the quality of generated text relative to reference outputs.","t12-13":"Inference cost tracking per user segment reveals whether AI economics are viable across the customer base.","t12-14":"Model performance monitoring requires population-level statistics (distribution shift, accuracy degradation) not just per-request logging.","t12-15":"Revenue per inference is the key unit economic metric for AI API products — it must exceed cost per inference to be sustainable.","t13-01":"LLM product design requires a new mental model: outputs are probabilistic distributions, not deterministic functions — design for variance.","t13-02":"The prompt-product interface is a new UX layer: prompt design, context management, and output formatting are core product decisions.","t13-03":"Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) architecture: retrieve relevant documents, augment the prompt, generate grounded response.","t13-04":"LLM fine-tuning changes model behavior permanently; prompt engineering is reversible — choose fine-tuning only for stable, well-defined tasks.","t13-05":"Output validation layers (guardrails, classifiers, schema enforcement) are essential reliability infrastructure for LLM products.","t13-06":"The AI UX paradox: users want magical results but need predictable behavior — design for explainability without sacrificing delight.","t13-07":"Agent architectures combine LLM reasoning, tool use, and memory — each component requires its own reliability and safety specification.","t13-08":"Few-shot examples in prompts dramatically improve output quality for structured tasks — a low-cost way to steer model behavior.","t13-09":"Streaming responses (token-by-token rendering) improve perceived latency and user experience without changing actual generation speed.","t13-10":"Context management strategy — what to include, compress, or summarise in the prompt — is a core LLM product engineering decision.","t13-11":"LLM safety layers: input filtering, output filtering, and behavioral fine-tuning provide defense-in-depth against misuse.","t13-12":"Multi-turn conversation state management requires explicit memory design — LLMs have no persistent state between API calls.","t13-13":"Structured output (JSON mode, function calling) makes LLM outputs machine-parseable — essential for downstream automation.","t13-14":"Model versioning strategy: pin model versions in production to prevent unexpected behavior changes from provider model updates.","t13-15":"Evaluation-driven development for LLM products: build the eval suite first, then iterate on prompts and models against it.","t14-01":"Data strategy for AI products: proprietary data compounds into model performance advantages that are hard for competitors to replicate.","t14-02":"Data governance frameworks (cataloguing, lineage, access controls, quality SLAs) are prerequisites for reliable AI product development.","t14-03":"Feature stores centralise ML features for reuse across models, reducing redundancy and ensuring training-serving consistency.","t14-04":"The data flywheel: more users → more interactions → richer training signal → better model → more users. Speed of iteration matters.","t14-05":"Synthetic data generation can augment scarce real data but risks introducing distribution shift — always validate on real-world distributions.","t14-06":"Data versioning (DVC, Delta Lake) enables reproducible ML experiments by snapshotting datasets alongside model versions.","t14-07":"Privacy-preserving ML techniques (federated learning, differential privacy, synthetic data) enable compliance without sacrificing model quality.","t14-08":"Training-serving skew occurs when feature distributions differ between training and production — a leading cause of silent model degradation.","t14-09":"Data labelling quality directly determines model ceiling — invest in inter-annotator agreement measurement and label auditing.","t14-10":"Active learning selects the most informative unlabelled examples for annotation, maximising model improvement per labelling dollar.","t14-11":"Data product thinking: treat datasets as first-class products with owners, SLAs, consumers, and quality metrics.","t14-12":"Streaming data pipelines (Kafka, Flink) enable real-time feature computation, unlocking time-sensitive AI use cases.","t14-13":"The 80/20 rule of ML: 80% of effort is data preparation, validation, and pipeline engineering — not modelling.","t14-14":"Zero-shot generalisation measures how well a model trained on one distribution performs on unseen distributions — a proxy for data diversity.","t14-15":"Data mesh architecture distributes data ownership to domain teams, improving data quality and reducing central bottlenecks.","t15-01":"Human-AI collaboration design requires explicit handoff points where humans can inspect, correct, and override AI outputs.","t15-02":"AI onboarding UX should calibrate user mental models: users who understand AI limitations make better decisions and report higher satisfaction.","t15-03":"Progressive disclosure in AI UX: surface AI confidence and reasoning incrementally to avoid overwhelming users with uncertainty.","t15-04":"Automation bias is the tendency to over-trust AI recommendations — design for appropriate reliance by making AI reasoning visible.","t15-05":"AI feedback loops in UX: implicit signals (clicks, dwell time, corrections) are higher-volume but noisier than explicit ratings.","t15-06":"Error recovery UX for AI: graceful failure messages, fallback flows, and undo capabilities reduce frustration when AI makes mistakes.","t15-07":"Adaptive AI interfaces personalise based on user behavior over time — requiring careful design to avoid filter bubbles and over-fitting to noise.","t15-08":"Explainability UX: 'why did AI do this?' explanations improve trust and enable users to correct systematic errors.","t15-09":"AI feature discoverability requires proactive surfacing — users rarely explore menus to find AI capabilities independently.","t15-10":"User mental models of AI lag behind actual capabilities — ongoing education through tooltips, examples, and feedback improves utilisation.","t15-11":"Consent and control UX: users should be able to opt out of AI features and understand how their data is used to train models.","t15-12":"The uncanny valley effect in AI UX: near-human but imperfect responses create more discomfort than obviously automated ones.","t15-13":"Collaborative filtering and content-based recommendations have opposite cold-start profiles — hybrid approaches are standard in production.","t15-14":"Cognitive load in AI-assisted decisions: too many AI suggestions can paradoxically reduce decision quality — less is often more.","t15-15":"Voice and multimodal AI UX introduces new affordances (hands-free, ambient) and constraints (no visual feedback) requiring distinct design patterns.","t16-01":"Sequential testing (always-valid inference) enables continuous monitoring of A/B tests without inflating false positive rates.","t16-02":"Interference effects in A/B tests (SUTVA violations) occur when treatment of one unit affects another — common in social and marketplace products.","t16-03":"Variance reduction techniques (CUPED, stratification) decrease the sample size required to detect a given effect size.","t16-04":"Novelty effects cause users to engage more with any change initially — holdout designs with long observation windows control for this.","t16-05":"Bayesian experimentation provides intuitive posterior probability estimates and enables early stopping with controlled error rates.","t16-06":"Factorial designs test multiple factors simultaneously, revealing interaction effects that sequential A/B tests would miss.","t16-07":"The minimum detectable effect (MDE) determines required sample size — smaller effects require exponentially more users to detect reliably.","t16-08":"Surrogate metrics are leading indicators correlated with long-term outcomes, enabling faster experimentation cycles.","t16-09":"Instrumentation debt accumulates when logging is inconsistent — it silently corrupts experiment results and is expensive to remediate.","t16-10":"Trigger analysis identifies the subpopulation of users who actually encountered the experimental treatment, increasing statistical sensitivity.","t16-11":"The multiple comparisons problem inflates false positive rates when testing many metrics — Bonferroni correction or FDR control is required.","t16-12":"Interleaving experiments (search ranking, recommendations) detect preference signals with 100x fewer users than A/B tests.","t16-13":"Holdout groups (long-term holdouts) measure cumulative and network effects that standard two-week A/B windows miss.","t16-14":"Experiment velocity — the number of validated learnings per unit time — is a leading indicator of product organisation effectiveness.","t16-15":"Causal inference methods (DiD, synthetic control, IV) enable quasi-experimental learning when randomisation is infeasible.","t17-01":"The alignment problem: as AI systems become more capable, ensuring their goals remain aligned with human values becomes harder, not easier.","t17-02":"Goodhart's Law applies to AI safety: reward models trained on human preferences can be gamed by sufficiently capable optimisers.","t17-03":"Interpretability research aims to make AI reasoning transparent, enabling humans to audit and correct model behavior before deployment.","t17-04":"The orthogonality thesis: any level of intelligence is compatible with almost any goal — intelligence alone does not guarantee aligned values.","t17-05":"Containment strategies (capability limitations, sandboxing, tripwires) reduce the risk of unsafe behavior from powerful AI systems.","t17-06":"Value learning approaches (IRL, RLHF, cooperative AI) infer human preferences from behavior rather than explicit specification.","t17-07":"Deceptive alignment is the scenario where a model behaves safely during training but pursues different goals at deployment — a key concern.","t17-08":"The treacherous turn refers to an AI that waits until it has sufficient capability before acting against human interests — a theoretical risk.","t17-09":"Red-teaming and adversarial probing systematically discover failure modes in AI systems before they are encountered in production.","t17-10":"Debate as a safety technique: two AI agents argue opposing positions, with a human judge determining truth — leveraging AI to oversee AI.","t17-11":"Scalable oversight addresses the challenge of supervising AI on tasks that exceed human ability to directly evaluate.","t17-12":"Robustness to distribution shift is a prerequisite for safe AI deployment — models that fail silently on out-of-distribution inputs are dangerous.","t17-13":"The principal-agent problem in AI: the AI (agent) may not faithfully pursue the goals of the humans (principals) who deployed it.","t17-14":"Corrigibility — the property of accepting correction and shutdown — is a foundational safety property that must be preserved during training.","t17-15":"Proactive safety involves AI systems actively supporting human oversight mechanisms, not merely tolerating them.","t18-01":"Multimodal foundation models (GPT-4V, Gemini) enable cross-modal reasoning — analysing images with text context or generating images from descriptions.","t18-02":"Cross-modal alignment training links visual and textual representations, enabling zero-shot image classification via natural language.","t18-03":"Video understanding models must reason over temporal sequences, requiring architectures that capture motion and causality.","t18-04":"The modality gap in multimodal models refers to the separation between visual and textual embedding spaces — bridged by contrastive training.","t18-05":"Multimodal RAG retrieves relevant images or documents alongside text, providing richer context for generation tasks.","t18-06":"Speech-to-text (ASR) and text-to-speech (TTS) models enable voice interfaces; disfluency handling and speaker diarisation are key production challenges.","t18-07":"Vision-language models require careful evaluation on both unimodal and cross-modal benchmarks to detect capability and safety gaps.","t18-08":"Multimodal hallucination occurs when models generate text inconsistent with image content — distinct from text-only hallucination.","t18-09":"Diffusion models generate images by iteratively denoising from random noise — enabling photorealistic synthesis and editing.","t18-10":"Embodied AI systems must integrate perception, reasoning, and action in real-time — latency and reliability constraints differ fundamentally from text AI.","t18-11":"Multimodal product design must account for modality-specific latency (image encoding is slower than text tokenisation) in user-facing features.","t18-12":"Audio foundation models (Whisper, MusicGen) open new product categories in transcription, dubbing, and generative audio.","t18-13":"Grounding in vision-language models links linguistic expressions to specific image regions — enabling precise visual question answering.","t18-14":"The eval gap for multimodal models: benchmarks lag behind capabilities, requiring PM-led evaluation design for product-specific quality assessment.","t18-15":"Multimodal safety requires both text and image safety pipelines — adversarial inputs can exploit modality boundaries to bypass single-modality filters.","t19-01":"AI platform PMs must balance developer experience (DX) with model capability — poor DX is a leading cause of platform churn.","t19-02":"API design for AI platforms requires versioning strategies that allow model updates without breaking downstream integrations.","t19-03":"The AI platform adoption ladder: experiment → prototype → production → scale. Each stage has distinct failure modes and PM interventions.","t19-04":"Compute orchestration (auto-scaling, spot instances, batching) is a core platform PM responsibility for managing inference economics.","t19-05":"Developer relations (DevRel) for AI platforms is a product function: documentation, SDKs, and example apps directly drive adoption metrics.","t19-06":"AI platform trust requires transparency about model updates, performance degradations, and breaking changes — treat the changelog as a product.","t19-07":"Multi-tenancy in AI platforms requires careful isolation of fine-tuned models, data, and usage quotas across customers.","t19-08":"The platform PM's build-vs.-integrate decision: build differentiated capabilities, integrate commoditised ones — the boundary shifts as the market matures.","t19-09":"Rate limiting and quota management in AI APIs are product decisions: they shape developer economics, abuse prevention, and growth patterns.","t19-10":"Observability for AI platforms includes model-level metrics (latency, throughput, error rates) and application-level metrics (task completion, quality scores).","t19-11":"Ecosystem strategy for AI platforms: invest in integrations with high-traffic developer tools (IDEs, notebooks, CI/CD) to embed deeply in workflows.","t19-12":"AI platform pricing models (per-token, per-call, subscription, outcome-based) each create different developer incentives and platform economics.","t19-13":"Fine-tuning APIs are a platform differentiation lever: enabling customers to train specialised models on their data creates high switching costs.","t19-14":"Safety and moderation APIs are table-stakes for AI platforms — developers need programmatic access to content filtering to build compliant products.","t19-15":"The AI platform competitive moat: network effects from developer ecosystems, proprietary training data, and infrastructure scale advantages compound over time.","t20-01":"Transformative AI (TAI) refers to systems that could fundamentally restructure economies and societies — distinct from narrow automation.","t20-02":"The intelligence explosion hypothesis (Bostrom, Good) posits that once AI can improve its own design, capability growth becomes recursive and rapid.","t20-03":"Economic disruption from AGI could be more rapid than historical technology transitions, challenging existing redistribution and retraining mechanisms.","t20-04":"Coordination failures in AI development — racing dynamics, information asymmetries — may produce worse global outcomes than cooperative development.","t20-05":"Differential technological development prioritises safety and governance research relative to capabilities — a key strategic policy lever.","t20-06":"The governance gap: AI capabilities are advancing faster than regulatory frameworks, creating accountability voids that PMs must navigate proactively.","t20-07":"Multipolar AGI futures (multiple comparable systems) may offer safety advantages over monopolar outcomes but introduce coordination challenges.","t20-08":"The strategic value of AI safety research is dual-use: it produces better, more reliable products while reducing catastrophic risk.","t20-09":"Scenario planning for transformative AI: map product roadmap decisions to plausible AGI timelines (2-5 years, 5-15 years, 15+ years).","t20-10":"The AI rights question will become increasingly relevant as systems demonstrate sophisticated goal-directed behavior — a long-term PM consideration.","t20-11":"Compute governance (export controls, thresholds, reporting) is the primary policy lever for regulating frontier AI development.","t20-12":"Proactive safety contributions by AI PMs include advocating for evals, red-teaming, staged rollouts, and internal safety culture.","t20-13":"The PM's role in an AGI transition: build human-AI collaboration patterns that preserve meaningful human agency and decision authority.","t20-14":"Existential risk from AI is taken seriously by leading researchers — PMs at frontier labs have direct influence on safety culture and practices.","t20-15":"The most important PM skill for the AGI era: epistemic humility — maintaining calibrated uncertainty about system capabilities and failure modes."};

